228
00:13:33.980 --> 00:13:37.020
 I'd love to come back to the concept of jagged intelligence in a little bit.

229
00:13:37.500 --> 00:13:47.600
 If you were a founder today and thinking about building a company, you are trying to solve a problem that you think is tractable, something that is a domain that is verifiable.

230
00:13:47.600 --> 00:13:58.660
 But you look around and you think, oh, my gosh, well, the labs have really, really started getting to escape velocity in the ones that seem most obvious, math, coding, and others.

231
00:13:58.920 --> 00:14:01.580
 What would your advice be to the founders in the audience?

232
00:14:05.960 --> 00:14:12.420
 So I think maybe that comes to the previous question of, I do think that verifiability, because it, let me think.

233
00:14:12.420 --> 00:14:18.420
 So verifiability makes something tractable in the current paradigm, because you can throw a huge amount of RL at it.

234
00:14:20.220 --> 00:14:25.740
 So maybe one way to see it is that that remains true even if the labs are not focusing on it directly.

235
00:14:25.920 --> 00:14:34.040
 So if you are in a verifiable setting where you could create these RL environments or examples, then that actually sets you up to potentially do your own fine-tuning, and you might benefit from that.

236
00:14:34.200 --> 00:14:36.100
 But that is fundamentally technology that just works.

237
00:14:36.180 --> 00:14:36.860
 You can pull a lever.

238
00:14:36.860 --> 00:14:46.820
 If you have a huge amount of diverse data sets of RL environments, et cetera, you can use your favorite fine-tuning framework and pull the lever and get something that actually works pretty well.

239
00:14:47.340 --> 00:14:50.600
 So I don't know what the examples of this might be.

240
00:14:51.720 --> 00:14:57.720
 But I do think there are some very valuable reinforcement learning environments that people could think of that I think are not part of the...

241
00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:04.780
 Yeah, I don't want to give away the answer, but there is one domain that I think is very, oh, okay, sorry.

242
00:15:04.880 --> 00:15:08.720
 I don't mean to vague post on the stage, but there are some examples of this.

243
00:15:08.960 --> 00:15:12.980
 On the flip side, what do you think still feels automatable, only from a distance?

244
00:15:14.540 --> 00:15:19.580
 I do think that ultimately almost everything can be made verifiable to some extent.

245
00:15:19.720 --> 00:15:24.780
 Some things easier than others, because even for things like writing or so on,

246
00:15:24.780 --> 00:15:32.700
 you can imagine having a council of LLM judges and probably get something reasonable from this kind of an approach.

247
00:15:32.840 --> 00:15:34.760
 So it's more about what's easy or hard.

248
00:15:36.140 --> 00:15:44.060
 So I do think that ultimately, yeah, I think everything is automatable.

249
00:15:45.300 --> 00:15:46.040
 Amazing, okay.

250
00:15:46.480 --> 00:15:52.200
 So last year you coined the term vibe coding, and today we're in a world that feels a little bit more serious, more organic engineering.

251
00:15:52.200 --> 00:15:56.320
 What do you think is the difference between the two, and what would you actually call what we're in today?

252
00:15:57.320 --> 00:16:02.320
 Yeah, so I would say vibe coding is about raising the floor for everyone in terms of what they can do in software.

253
00:16:02.700 --> 00:16:06.780
 So the floor rises, everyone can vibe code anything, and that's amazing, incredible.

254
00:16:07.100 --> 00:16:12.380
 But then I would say agentic engineering is about preserving the quality bar of what existed before in professional software.

255
00:16:12.640 --> 00:16:16.200
 So you're not allowed to introduce vulnerabilities due to vibe coding.

256
00:16:18.080 --> 00:16:21.720
 You're still responsible for your software, just as before, but can you go faster?

257
00:16:22.080 --> 00:16:25.180
 And spoiler is you can, but how do you do that properly?

258
00:16:25.600 --> 00:16:30.000
 And so to me, agentic engineering, I call it that because I do think it's kind of like an engineering discipline.

259
00:16:30.260 --> 00:16:32.540
 You have these agents, which are these like spiky entities.

260
00:16:32.540 --> 00:16:35.800
 They're a bit fallible, a little bit stochastic, but they are extremely powerful.

261
00:16:35.800 --> 00:16:40.940
 And it's how do you coordinate them to go faster without sacrificing your quality bar?

262
00:16:41.280 --> 00:16:47.000
 And doing that well and correctly is the realm of agentic engineering.

263
00:16:48.100 --> 00:16:49.560
 So I kind of see them as different.

264
00:16:49.760 --> 00:16:54.060
 Like one is about maybe raising the floor, and the other is about extrapolating.

265
00:16:54.180 --> 00:17:00.040
 And what I'm seeing, I think, is there is a very high ceiling on agentic engineer capability.

266
00:17:00.040 --> 00:17:03.160
 And, you know, people used to talk about the 10x engineer previously.

267
00:17:03.280 --> 00:17:05.460
 I think that this has magnified a lot more.

268
00:17:06.040 --> 00:17:09.480
 10x is not the speed up you gain.

269
00:17:10.380 --> 00:17:18.100
 And I think it does seem to me like people who are very good at this peak a lot more than 10x from my perspective right now.

270
00:17:18.240 --> 00:17:19.240
 I really like that framing.

271
00:17:20.500 --> 00:17:27.940
 One thing that when Sam Allman came to AI Ascent last year, one memorable thing he said was that people of different generations use ChatGPT differently.

272
00:17:27.940 --> 00:17:31.400
 So if you're in your 30s, you use it as a Google search replacement.

273
00:17:31.600 --> 00:17:35.100
 But if you're in your teens, ChatGPT is your gateway to the Internet.

274
00:17:35.420 --> 00:17:37.840
 What is the parallel here in coding today?

275
00:17:37.840 --> 00:17:49.500
 If we were to watch two people code using OpenClaw, CloudCode, CodeX, one you'd consider mediocre at it, and one you would consider fully AI native, how would you describe the difference?

276
00:17:51.340 --> 00:17:59.820
 I mean, I think it's just trying to get the most out of the tools that are available, utilizing all of their features, investing into your own kind of setup.

277
00:18:00.380 --> 00:18:04.400
 So just like previously, all the engineers are used to basically getting the most out of the tools you use.

278
00:18:04.500 --> 00:18:09.340
 Either it's Vim or VS Code, or now it's, you know, CloudCode or Codex or so on.

279
00:18:09.340 --> 00:18:17.740
 So just investing into your setup and utilizing a lot of the, you know, tools that are available to you.

280
00:18:19.060 --> 00:18:20.840
 And I think it just kind of looks like that.

281
00:18:21.040 --> 00:18:31.980
 I do think that maybe related thought is a lot of people are maybe hiring for this, right, because they want to hire strong agentic engineers.

282
00:18:31.980 --> 00:18:43.220
 I do think that what I'm seeing is that, you know, most people have still not refactored their hiring process for agentic engineer capability, right?

283
00:18:43.480 --> 00:18:47.020
 Like if you're giving out puzzles to solve, then this is still the old paradigm.

284
00:18:47.220 --> 00:18:53.060
 I would say that hiring has to look like give me a really big project and see someone implement that big project.

285
00:18:53.060 --> 00:19:03.820
 Like let's write, say, a Twitter clone for agents and then make it really good, make it really secure, and then have some agents simulate some activity on this Twitter.

286
00:19:04.180 --> 00:19:13.140
 And then I'm going to use 10 Codex 5.4 X high to try to break your website that you deployed.

287
00:19:13.520 --> 00:19:16.940
 And they're going to try to basically break it, and they should not be able to break it.

288
00:19:17.140 --> 00:19:18.800
 And so maybe it looks like that, right?

289
00:19:18.800 --> 00:19:28.220
 And so, yeah, watching people in that setting and building bigger projects and utilizing the tooling is maybe what I would look at for the most part.

290
00:19:28.660 --> 00:19:33.680
 And as agents do more, what human skill do you think becomes more valuable, not less?

291
00:19:35.120 --> 00:19:36.440
 So, yeah, it's a good question.

292
00:19:36.620 --> 00:19:41.480
 I think, well, right now the answer is that the agents are kind of like these intern entities, right?

293
00:19:41.480 --> 00:19:43.380
 So it's remarkable.

294
00:19:44.820 --> 00:19:50.580
 You basically still have to be in charge of the aesthetics, the judgment, the taste, and a little bit of oversight.

295
00:19:50.820 --> 00:19:56.440
 Maybe one of my favorite examples of, like, the weirdness of agents is for Menugen.

296
00:19:56.720 --> 00:20:02.440
 You sign up with a Google account, but you purchase credits using a Stripe account.

297
00:20:02.440 --> 00:20:02.560
 You sign up with a Google account.

298
00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:01.280
 and both of them have email addresses.

299
00:20:01.800 --> 00:20:03.580
 And my agent actually tries to basically,

300
00:20:06.040 --> 00:20:07.380
 like when you purchase credits,

301
00:20:07.600 --> 00:20:10.300
 it assigned it using the email address from Stripe

302
00:20:10.300 --> 00:20:12.280
 to the Google email address.

303
00:20:12.440 --> 00:20:16.200
 Like there wasn't a persistent user ID for people.

304
00:20:16.400 --> 00:20:18.100
 It was trying to match up the email addresses

305
00:20:18.100 --> 00:20:19.380
 but you could use different email address

306
00:20:19.380 --> 00:20:20.400
 for your Stripe and your Google

307
00:20:20.400 --> 00:20:23.240
 and basically would not associate the funds.

308
00:20:23.560 --> 00:20:24.700
 And so this is the kind of thing

309
00:20:24.700 --> 00:20:27.100
 that these agents still will make mistakes about.

310
00:20:27.260 --> 00:20:28.680
 It's like, why would you use email addresses

311
00:20:28.680 --> 00:20:30.040
 to try to cross correlate the funds?

312
00:20:30.200 --> 00:20:31.020
 They can be arbitrary.

313
00:20:31.220 --> 00:20:32.580
 You can use different emails, et cetera.

314
00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:34.760
 Like this is such a weird thing to do.

315
00:20:34.940 --> 00:20:37.580
 So I think people have to be in charge of this spec,

316
00:20:37.800 --> 00:20:41.400
 this plan, and I actually don't even like the plan mode.

317
00:20:41.580 --> 00:20:43.820
 I would, I mean, obviously it's very useful

318
00:20:43.820 --> 00:20:45.240
 but I think there's something more general here

319
00:20:45.240 --> 00:20:46.700
 where you have to work with your agent

320
00:20:46.700 --> 00:20:48.580
 to design a spec that is very detailed

321
00:20:48.580 --> 00:20:51.200
 and maybe it's basically the docs

322
00:20:51.200 --> 00:20:53.120
 and then get the agents to write them.

323
00:20:53.220 --> 00:20:54.620
 And you're in charge of the oversight

324
00:20:54.620 --> 00:20:56.260
 and the top level categories

325
00:20:56.760 --> 00:20:58.280
 but the agents are doing a lot of the under the hood.

326
00:20:58.680 --> 00:21:01.440
 And so I think you're not caring about some of the details.

327
00:21:01.700 --> 00:21:05.120
 So as an example also with arrays or tensors

328
00:21:05.120 --> 00:21:08.240
 in neural networks, there's a ton of details

329
00:21:08.240 --> 00:21:09.700
 between PyTorch and NumPy

330
00:21:09.700 --> 00:21:11.320
 and all the different like pandas and so on

331
00:21:11.320 --> 00:21:13.060
 for all the different little API details.

332
00:21:13.260 --> 00:21:16.460
 And I already forgot about the keep dims versus keep dim

333
00:21:16.460 --> 00:21:18.440
 or whether it's dim or axis or reshape

334
00:21:18.440 --> 00:21:19.460
 or permute or transpose.

335
00:21:19.680 --> 00:21:20.900
 I don't remember this stuff anymore, right?

336
00:21:21.060 --> 00:21:21.820
 Because you don't have to.

337
00:21:22.020 --> 00:21:24.000
 This is the kind of details that are handled by the intern

338
00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:25.340
 because they have very good recall.

339
00:21:25.760 --> 00:21:27.520
 But you still have to know, for example,

340
00:21:27.700 --> 00:21:31.220
 that there's underlying tensor, there's an underlying view,

341
00:21:31.500 --> 00:21:33.760
 and then you can manipulate view of the same storage

342
00:21:33.760 --> 00:21:34.920
 or you can have different storage

343
00:21:34.920 --> 00:21:36.120
 which should be less efficient.

344
00:21:36.360 --> 00:21:37.720
 And so you still have to have an understanding

345
00:21:37.720 --> 00:21:40.700
 of what this stuff is doing and some of the fundamentals

346
00:21:41.820 --> 00:21:44.720
 so that you're not copying memory around unnecessarily and so on.

347
00:21:44.720 --> 00:21:48.340
 But the details of the APIs are not handed off.

348
00:21:48.620 --> 00:21:51.860
 So you're in charge of the taste, the engineering, the design,

349
00:21:52.400 --> 00:21:54.920
 and that it makes sense, and that you're asking for the right things,

350
00:21:54.980 --> 00:21:57.820
 and that you're saying that, okay, these have to be unique user IDs

351
00:21:57.820 --> 00:21:58.880
 that we're going to tie everything to.

352
00:22:00.280 --> 00:22:03.160
 And so you're doing some of the design and development

353
00:22:03.160 --> 00:22:05.040
 and the engineers are doing the fill in the blanks.

354
00:22:05.220 --> 00:22:06.840
 And that's currently kind of like where we are,

355
00:22:06.920 --> 00:22:09.020
 and I think that's what everyone, of course, is seeing,

356
00:22:09.140 --> 00:22:10.140
 I think, right now.

357
00:22:10.140 --> 00:22:14.080
 Do you think there's a chance that this taste and judgment

358
00:22:14.080 --> 00:22:17.220
 matters less over time, or will the ceiling just keep rising?

359
00:22:18.260 --> 00:22:19.160
 Yeah, it's a good question.

360
00:22:19.320 --> 00:22:25.480
 I would say, I mean, I'm hoping that it improves.

361
00:22:25.620 --> 00:22:28.000
 I think probably the reason it doesn't improve right now is,

362
00:22:28.080 --> 00:22:29.220
 again, it's not part of the RL.

363
00:22:29.420 --> 00:22:32.380
 There's probably no aesthetics cost or reward,

364
00:22:32.500 --> 00:22:34.600
 or it's not good enough or something like that.

365
00:22:36.600 --> 00:22:38.460
 I do think that when you actually look at the code,

366
00:22:38.560 --> 00:22:39.960
 sometimes I get a little bit of a heart attack

367
00:22:39.960 --> 00:22:43.160
 because it's not like super amazing code necessarily all the time,

368
00:22:43.260 --> 00:22:44.920
 and it's very bloaty, and there's a lot of copy-paste,

369
00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:46.820
 and there's awkward abstractions that are brittle,

370
00:22:47.020 --> 00:22:49.540
 and like it works, but it's just really gross.

371
00:22:50.880 --> 00:22:53.760
 And I do hope that this can improve in future models.

372
00:22:54.160 --> 00:22:57.560
 A good example also is this micro-GPT project,

373
00:22:57.860 --> 00:23:00.520
 where I was trying to simplify LLM training

374
00:23:00.520 --> 00:23:01.860
 to be as simple as possible.

375
00:23:02.100 --> 00:23:03.140
 The models hate this.

376
00:23:03.240 --> 00:23:04.020
 They can't do it.

377
00:23:04.140 --> 00:23:07.700
 I kept trying to prompt an LLM to simplify more,

378
00:23:07.760 --> 00:23:09.380
 simplify more, and it just can't,

379
00:23:09.940 --> 00:23:12.140
 you feel like you're outside of the RL circuits.

380
00:23:12.420 --> 00:23:14.080
 It feels like you're obviously,

381
00:23:14.680 --> 00:23:15.840
 you know, you're pulling teeth.

382
00:23:16.080 --> 00:23:17.540
 It's not like light speed.

383
00:23:18.400 --> 00:23:22.220
 So I do think that people still remain in charge of this,

384
00:23:22.320 --> 00:23:23.900
 but I do think that there's nothing fundamental,

385
00:23:23.900 --> 00:23:24.840
 again, that's preventing it.

386
00:23:24.920 --> 00:23:26.340
 It's just the labs haven't done it yet almost.

387
00:23:27.620 --> 00:23:32.720
 So I'd love to come back to this idea of jagged forms of intelligence.

388
00:23:33.080 --> 00:23:36.040
 You wrote a little bit about this with a very thought-provoking piece

389
00:23:36.040 --> 00:23:37.420
 around animals versus ghosts,

390
00:23:38.240 --> 00:23:40.880
 and the idea is that we're not building animals.

391
00:23:40.880 --> 00:23:42.140
 We are summoning ghosts,

392
00:23:42.660 --> 00:23:47.880
 and these are jagged forms of intelligence that are shaped by data and reward functions,

393
00:23:47.880 --> 00:23:52.040
 but not by intrinsic motivation or fun or curiosity or empowerment,

394
00:23:53.280 --> 00:23:55.860
 things that kind of came about via evolution.

395
00:23:56.860 --> 00:24:04.440
 Why does that framing matter, and what does it actually change about how you build and deploy and evaluate or even trust them?

396
00:24:06.340 --> 00:24:12.520
 Yeah, so, yeah, I think the reason I wrote about this is because I'm trying to wrap my head around what these things are, right?

397
00:24:12.640 --> 00:24:14.920
 Because if you have a good model of what they are or are not,

398
00:24:15.020 --> 00:24:17.360
 then you're going to be more competent at using them.

399
00:24:18.420 --> 00:24:21.380
 And I do think that, I don't know if it has,

400
00:24:21.960 --> 00:24:24.520
 I'm not sure if it actually has like real power.

401
00:24:25.340 --> 00:24:27.120
 I think it's a little bit of philosophizing,

402
00:24:28.520 --> 00:24:29.720
 but I do think that,

403
00:24:31.580 --> 00:24:34.420
 I think it's just coming to terms with the fact that

404
00:24:34.420 --> 00:24:36.500
 these things are not, you know, animal intelligences.

405
00:24:36.660 --> 00:24:37.540
 Like if you yell at them,

406
00:24:37.580 --> 00:24:39.360
 they're not going to work better or worse,

407
00:24:39.420 --> 00:24:40.560
 or it doesn't have any impact.

408
00:24:42.620 --> 00:24:45.760
 And it's all just kind of like these statistical simulation circuits

409
00:24:46.460 --> 00:24:49.260
 where the substrate is pre-training,

410
00:24:49.380 --> 00:24:50.400
 so like statistics,

411
00:24:50.940 --> 00:24:53.180
 and then, but then there's RL bolting on top,

412
00:24:53.240 --> 00:24:55.860
 so it kind of like increases the appendages.

413
00:24:56.620 --> 00:24:57.960
 And maybe it's just kind of like,

414
00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:04.200
 a mindset of what I'm coming into or what's likely to work or not likely to work or how

415
00:25:04.200 --> 00:25:08.480
 to modify it. But I don't actually, I don't know that I have like, here are the five obvious

416
00:25:08.480 --> 00:25:12.480
 outcomes of how to make your system better. It's more just being suspicious of it and

417
00:25:13.340 --> 00:25:18.120
 figuring it out over time. That's where it starts. Okay, so you are so deep in working

418
00:25:18.120 --> 00:25:23.200
 with agents that don't just chat. They have real permissions. They have local context.

419
00:25:23.500 --> 00:25:28.180
 They actually take action on your behalf. What does the world look like when we all start

420
00:25:28.180 --> 00:25:34.700
 to live in that world? Yeah, I think a lot of people probably here are excited about what

421
00:25:34.700 --> 00:25:40.280
 this native agentic environment looks like. And everything has to be rewritten. Everything

422
00:25:40.280 --> 00:25:45.300
 is still fundamentally written for humans and has to be moved around. I still use, most

423
00:25:45.300 --> 00:25:48.620
 of the time when I use different frameworks or libraries or things like that, they still

424
00:25:48.620 --> 00:25:52.920
 have docs that are fundamentally written for humans. This is my favorite pet peeve. Like

425
00:25:52.920 --> 00:25:56.980
 I don't, why are people still telling me what to do? Like I don't want to do anything. What

426
00:25:56.980 --> 00:26:02.680
 is the thing I should copy paste to my agent? Like, so it's just every time I'm told, you

427
00:26:02.680 --> 00:26:08.840
 know, go to this URL or something like that, it's just like, oh, you know. So everyone

428
00:26:08.840 --> 00:26:13.320
 is, I think, excited about how do we decompose the workloads that need to happen into fundamentally

429
00:26:13.320 --> 00:26:26.960
 sensors over the world, actuators over the world. How do we make it agent native? Basically

430
00:26:27.460 --> 00:26:32.620
 yeah, around data structures that are very legible to the LLMs. So I think, yeah, I'm hoping

431
00:26:32.620 --> 00:26:37.080
 that there's a lot of agent first infrastructure out there. And that, you know, for Menugen,

432
00:26:37.420 --> 00:26:41.080
 famously, when I wrote the, not, I'm not sure how famously, but when I wrote the blog post

433
00:26:41.080 --> 00:26:46.300
 about Menugen, a lot of the work, or a lot of the trouble was not even writing the code

434
00:26:46.300 --> 00:26:49.380
 for Menugen. It was deploying it in Vercel because I had to work with all these different

435
00:26:49.380 --> 00:26:53.660
 services and I just string them up and I had to go to their settings and the menus and, you

436
00:26:53.660 --> 00:26:58.580
 know, configure my DNS and it was just so annoying. And so that's a good example of,

437
00:26:58.660 --> 00:27:03.640
 I would hope that Menugen, that I could give a prompt to an LLM, build Menugen, and that

438
00:27:03.640 --> 00:27:08.020
 I didn't have to touch anything and it's deployed in that same way on the internet. I think that

439
00:27:08.020 --> 00:27:12.340
 would be a good kind of a test for whether or not a lot of our infrastructure is becoming

440
00:27:12.340 --> 00:27:16.640
 more and more agent native. And then ultimately I would say, yeah, I do think we're going towards

441
00:27:16.640 --> 00:27:21.360
 a world where there's agent representation for people and for organizations.

442
00:27:23.640 --> 00:27:27.840
 And, you know, I'll have my agent talk to your agent to figure out some of the details

443
00:27:27.840 --> 00:27:33.920
 of our meetings or things like that. So, I do think that that's roughly where things

444
00:27:33.920 --> 00:27:36.700
 are going. But, yeah, I think everyone here is excited about that.

445
00:27:36.840 --> 00:27:40.740
 I really like the visual analogy of sensors and actuators. I actually hadn't thought about

446
00:27:40.740 --> 00:27:41.640
 that. It's super interesting.

